        "content_QHFNfY": {
          "type": "content",
          "settings": {
            "title": "The Science Behind Mad Honey Effects",
            "subtitle": "",
            "description": "<p><a href=\"/pages/grayanotoxin\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"grayanotoxin\"><strong>Grayanotoxin</strong></a>, a potent natural neurotoxin is the active ingredient behind the effects of Mad Honey. Once the Grayanotoxin in Mad Honey reaches Gastrointestinal Tract it is absorbed and passes through intestinal membranes as it is Lipophilic. The grayanotoxin then enters the bloodstream by bypassing the liver and reaches excitable nerves as well as the heart. </p><p>Grayanotoxin in blood is absorbed at cellular level and starts affecting the body by blocking sodium ion channels within cell membranes thereby causing prolonged depolarization and cell excitation. This disruption in the transmission of the neurons potentially impacts on excited tissue including the central nervous system and muscle cells.<br/><br/></p>",
            "button_text": "",
            "button_link": "",
            "button_text_2": "",
            "button_link_2": ""
          }
        }
      },
